1. Moving Average Model


MA(1)

  • First order moving average process is defiend as: \[ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1}, \hspace15mm e_t \sim WN(0, \sigma^2) \] and \(\theta_1\) is real valued constant.


  • Compare this to the first order Autoregressive process \[ X_t - \phi_1 X_{t-1} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t \]


  • Using the backward operator, MA(1) can be written as \[ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \underbrace{ (1 - \theta_1 B) }_{\Theta(B) } \, e_t. \]


  • Watch the sign in front of \(\theta_1\)! This is Cryer’s convension. See ARIMA functions page of the website.



Mean of MA(1)

\[ \begin{align} E(X_t) &= \hspace3mm E(e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1}) \\\\ &= \hspace3mm E(e_t) - \theta_1 E(e_{t-1}) &= \hspace3mm 0 \end{align} \]



ACVF at lag 0

\[ \begin{align} \mbox{Var}(X_t) &= \hspace3mm \mbox{Var}(e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1})\\ \\ &= \hspace3mm \mbox{Var}(e_t) + \theta_1^2 \mbox{Var}(e_{t-1})\\ \\ &= \hspace3mm \sigma^2 + \theta_1^2 \sigma^2 \\ \\ &= \hspace3mm (1+\theta_1^2) \sigma^2 \end{align} \]



ACVF at lag 1

\[ \begin{align} \gamma(1) &= \hspace3mm \mbox{ Cov }(X_t, X_{t+1} ) \\ \\ &= \hspace3mm \mbox{ Cov }(e_t- \theta_1 e_{t-1}, \hspace3mm e_{t+1}-\theta_1 e_{t} )\\ \\ &= \hspace3mm \mbox{ Cov }(e_t , \, e_{t+1} ) - \mbox{ Cov }(e_t , \, \theta_1 e_{t} ) - \mbox{ Cov }(\theta_1 e_{t-1}, \, e_{t+1} ) + \mbox{ Cov }(\theta_1 e_{t-1}, \, \theta_1 e_{t} ) \\ \\ &= \hspace3mm -\theta_1 \mbox{ Cov }(e_t , \, e_{t} ) \\ \\ &= \hspace3mm -\theta_1 \, \sigma^2 \end{align} \]



ACVF at lag 2

\[ \begin{align} \gamma(2) &= \hspace3mm \mbox{ Cov }(Y_t, Y_{t+2} ) \\ \\ &= \hspace3mm \mbox{ Cov }(e_t- \theta_1 e_{t-1}, \hspace3mm e_{t+2}-\theta_1 e_{t+1} )\\ \\ &= \hspace3mm 0 \end{align} \]



ACVF and ACF of MA(1)

  • ACVF \[ \gamma(h) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} \sigma^2(1+\theta_1^2) & \mbox{ if } h=0 \\ -\sigma^2 \theta_1 & \mbox{ if } h= \pm 1 \\ 0 & \mbox{ if } |h|>1 \\ \end{array} \right. \]

  • ACF \[ \rho(h) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} 1 & \mbox{ if } h=0 \\ -\theta_1/ (1+\theta^2_1) & \mbox{ if } h= \pm 1 \\ 0 & \mbox{ if } |h|>1 \\ \end{array} \right. \]



MA(q)

  • Moving Average process of order \(q\) is \[ X_t = e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} - \theta_2 e_{t-2} - \cdots - \theta_q e_{t-q}, \] where \(e_t \sim WN(0,\sigma^2)\) and \(\theta_1, \ldots, \theta_q\) is real valued constant.

  • Using the backward operator, we write this as \[ X_t = (1 - \theta_1 B - \theta_2 B^2 - \cdots - \theta_q B^q) \, e_t. \]

  • We shorten the notation further, and write \[ X_t = \Theta(B) Z_t. \] where Characteristic Polinomial, \(\Theta(z) = (1 - \theta_1 z - \theta_2 z^2 - \cdots - \theta_q z^q)\).



Mean and Var of MA(q)

  • Mean \[ E(X_t) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm E(e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} - \theta_2 e_{t-2} - \cdots - \theta_q e_{t-q}) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm 0. \]

  • Variance \[ \begin{align} \mbox{Var}(X_t) &= \hspace3mm \mbox{Var}(e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} - \theta_2 e_{t-2} - \cdots - \theta_q e_{t-q}) \\\\ &= \hspace3mm \sigma^2 + \theta_1 \, \sigma^2 + \theta_2 \, \sigma^2 + \cdots + \theta_q \, \sigma^2 \\\\ &= \hspace3mm \Big(1 + \theta_1 + \theta_2 + \cdots + \theta_q \Big) \, \sigma^2 \end{align} \]



ACVF and ACF of MA(q)

\[ \begin{align} \gamma(h) &= \hspace3mm \mbox{ Cov }(X_t, \hspace3mm X_{t+h} )\\ &= \hspace3mm \mbox{ Cov }\Big(e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} - \theta_2 e_{t-2} - \cdots - \theta_q e_{t-q}, \hspace5mm e_{t+h} - \theta_1 e_{t-1+h} - \theta_2 e_{t-2+h} - \cdots - \theta_q e_{t-q+h}\Big) \end{align} \]

Theoretical ACVF: \[ \gamma(h) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} \sigma^2 (1+\theta_1^2 \cdots + \theta_q^2) & \mbox{ if } h=0 \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_1 + \theta_2 \theta_1 + \theta_3 \theta_2 + \cdots + \theta_{q-1} \theta_{q}) & \mbox{ if } h=1 \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_2 + \theta_3 \theta_1 + \cdots + \theta_{q-2} \theta_{q}) & \mbox{ if } h=2 \\ \vdots & \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_q ) & \mbox{ if } h=q \\ 0 & \mbox{ if } |h|>q\\ \end{array} \right. \]


Theoretical ACF: \[ \rho(h) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} 1 & \mbox{ if } h=0 \\ \gamma(h) / \gamma(0) & \mbox{ if } -q \leq h \leq q \\ 0 & \mbox{ if } |h|> q \\ \end{array} \right. \]



Theorem

Every stationary q-corr TS with mean 0 can be represented as MA(\(q\)) process.



Example: MA(3)


\[ X_t = e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} - \theta_2 e_{t-2} - \theta_3 e_{t-3} \]

\[ \gamma(h) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} \sigma^2 (1+\theta_1^2 +\theta_2^2 + \theta_3^2 ) & \mbox{ if } h=0 \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_1 + \theta_2 \theta_1 + \theta_3 \theta_2 ) & \mbox{ if } h=1 \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_2 + \theta_3 \theta_1 ) & \mbox{ if } h=2 \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_3 ) & \mbox{ if } h=3 \\ 0 & \mbox{ if } |h|> \\ \end{array} \right. \]

\[ \rho(h) = \gamma(h) / \gamma(0) \]

Watch the Sign!

#   [Cryer]'s sign convention is (1-phi B) Y_t = (1-theta) e_t.
#   [Brockwell]'s             is (1-phi B) Y_t = (1+theta) e_t.
#
#   For AR(1) (1-.5 B) Y_t = e_t,          ACF should be all positive.
#             (1+.5 B) Y_t = e_t,          ACF should be alternating in sign.
#
#   For MA(1)          Y_t = (1-.5 B) e_t  ACF at lag 1 should be negative
#                      Y_t = (1+.5 B) e_t  ACF at lag 1 should be positive

#--- Theoretical ACF and PACF of MA ---
#     ARMAacf() uses  sign of MA parameters like [Brockwell]:  Y_t = (1+theta B) e_t
    Theta = c(.2,  .3, .2,  .2)
    
    MArho1 <- ARMAacf(ma = Theta, lag.max=20, pacf=FALSE)
    MApacf1<- ARMAacf(ma = Theta, lag.max=20, pacf=TRUE)

    layout(matrix(1:2, 1,2))
    plot(0:20, MArho1, type="h", col="red");   abline(h=0)
    plot(1:20, MApacf1, type="h", col="red");   abline(h=0)

#--- Theoretical ACVF of MA
#
#   tacvfARMA() uses sign of MA parameters like [Cryer]:  Y_t = (1 - theta B) e_t
#

  library(ltsa)

  MAgam2 <- tacvfARMA(theta= c(.2, .3, .2, .2), maxLag=20, sigma2=1)  #- Theoretical ACVF
  MArho2 <- MAgam2/MAgam2[1]                                          #- Theoretical ACF

  plot(0:20, MArho2, type="h", col="red");   abline(h=0)



Simulation: MA(q)

  T1 = c(.5)
  T2 = c(.2, -.3, .2, -.2)
  T3 = c(.2,  .3, .2,  .2)
  T4 = c(-.2,  -.3, -.2,  -.2)
  
  Theta = T1

  # arima.sim() uses sign of MA parameters like [Brockwell]:  Y_t = (1+theta B) e_t

  x  <- arima.sim( list(ma = c(0.5) ), n=250    )
  MArho1 <- ARMAacf(ma = Theta, lag.max=20, pacf=FALSE)
  MApacf1<- ARMAacf(ma = Theta, lag.max=20, pacf=TRUE)

  plot(x, type="o");  abline(h=0)

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2) ) 
  acf(x);    lines(0:20, MArho1,  type="p", col="red")
  pacf(x);   lines(1:20, MApacf1, type="p", col="red")

  layout(1)



Characteristics of MA(q)

  • ACF cuts off at \(q\)

  • PACF tails off



Invertible Representation of MA(\(q\))

  • Suppose we have MA(1) model (watch the sign!) \[ X_t = e_t + \theta_1 e_{t-1} \] This is already a causal representation.

  • We can rewrite the equation and get \[ X_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t. \]

  • That means we can do the same for \(X_{t-1}\), and write \[ X_{t-1} - \theta_1 e_{t-2} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_{t-1} \] We can substitute this into \(e_{t-1}\) above.

  • Substituting this expression of \(e_{t-1}\) into the first equation, \[ X_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t. \\\\ X_t - \theta_1 \big(X_{t-1} - \theta_1 e_{t-2} \big) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t \\ \\ X_t - \theta_1 X_{t-1} - \theta_1^2 e_{t-2} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t \]

  • Repeat this \(n\) times, we get \[ X_t - \theta_1 X_{t-1} - \cdots - \theta_1^{n-1} X_{t-n+1} - \theta_1^n e_{t-n} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t \] If \(|\theta_1|<1\), then we can write \[ e_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \sum_{i=0}^\infty \theta_1^i \, X_{t-i} \] This is called invertible representation.

  • \[ e_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \sum_{i=0}^\infty \pi_i X_{t-i} \\ \\ \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm (\pi_0 + \pi_1 B + \pi_2 B^2 + \pi_3 B^3 + \cdots ) \, X_{t} \\ \\ \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \Pi(B) \, X_{t} \]

  • So for our MA(\(q\)) model \[ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \Theta(B) e_t \\ \\ \Pi(B) \, X_{t} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t \]

  • Very similar to causal representation in AR(\(p\)), we have identity, \[ \Pi(z) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \frac{1}{\Theta(z)} \] \[ (\pi_0 + \pi_1 z + \pi_2 z^2 + \pi_3 z^3 + \cdots ) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \frac{1}{(1+\theta_1 z + \theta_2 z^2 + \cdots + \theta_q z^q)} \]

  • We can calculate coefficients by moving all the polynomials to the left and matching \[ (1-\theta_1 z - \theta_2 z^2 - \cdots - \theta_q z^q)(\pi_0 + \pi_1 z + \pi_2 z^2 + \pi_3 z^3 + \cdots ) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm 1 \]

  • For example, if we have MA(1), \[ (1-\theta_1 z )(\pi_0 + \pi_1 z + \pi_2 z^2 + \pi_3 z^3 + \cdots ) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm 1 \]

  • To find out the coeffeicnets \(\pi_i\), we can match the order of \(z\). \[ \begin{align} \pi_0 &= \hspace3mm 1 \hspace15mm (\mbox{ coefficient without $z$ })\\ -\theta_1 \pi_0 + \pi_1 &= \hspace3mm 0 \hspace15mm (\mbox{ coefficient of $z$})\\ -\theta_1 \pi_1 + \pi_2 &= \hspace3mm 0 \hspace15mm (\mbox{ coefficient of $z^2$})\\ -\theta_1 \pi_2 + \pi_3 &= \hspace3mm 0 \hspace15mm (\mbox{ coefficient of $z^3$})\\ &\vdots& \end{align} \]

    \[ \begin{align} \pi_0 &= \hspace3mm 1 \\ \pi_1 &= \hspace3mm \theta_1 \pi_0 \\ \pi_2 &= \hspace3mm \theta_1 \pi_1 \\ \pi_3 &= \hspace3mm \theta_1 \pi_2 \\ &\vdots& \end{align} \]

    \[ \begin{align} \pi_0 &= \hspace3mm 1 \\ \pi_1 &= \hspace3mm \theta_1 \\ \pi_2 &= \hspace3mm \theta_1^2\\ \pi_3 &= \hspace3mm \theta_1^3\\ &\vdots& \end{align} \]



Invertible Representation of MA(1)

  • Now we get invertible representation for MA(1), \[ e_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \sum_{i=0}^\infty \pi_i \, X_{t-i} = \sum_{i=0}^\infty \theta_1^i \, X_{t-i}. \]

  • To write the today’s error (innovation) \(e_t\), we need infinetely many past observation \(X_{t-i}\).

  • When can we do this?



Invertibility Condition

  • If all roots of characteristic polynomial \[ \Theta(z) = 1 + \theta_1 z + \theta_2 z^2 + \cdots + \theta_q z^q \] is outside of the unit circle, then MA(\(q\)) admits a invertible representation.

  • Same as causal condition in AR(\(p\)).

  • Watch the sign! We have same sign as \(\Phi(z)\) in AR(\(p\)), because we started with Brockwell’s convention; \(X_t = e_t + \theta_1 e_{t-1}\).

  • We assume all MA(\(q\)) we deal with are invertible.



Why Invertibility Condition is Important

  • If we have MA(3) process, \[ X_t = e_t -\hat \theta_1 e_{t-1} -\hat \theta_2 e_{t-2} -\hat \theta_3 e_{t-3} \] with estimated parameter \(\hat \theta_i\), we want to get residuals \(\hat e_t\), and check their randomness.

  • In AR(\(p\)), this was intuitive. e.g. if we had AR(2), \[ X_t - \hat \phi_1 X_{t-1} - \hat \phi_2 X_{t-2} = \hat e_t \]

  • In MA(\(q\)), we must use invertible expression, \[ \hat e_t = \hat \pi_0 X_t + \hat \pi_1 X_{t-1} + \hat \pi_2 X_{t-2} + \cdots \]

  • The best 1-step linear predictor of AR(3) process was \[ \hat X(1) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \phi_1 X_n + \phi_2 X_{n-1} + \phi_3 X_{n-2}. \] This was intuitive since \[ X_{t+1} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \phi_1 X_n + \phi_2 X_{n-1} + \phi_3 X_{n-2} + e_{t+1}. \]

  • Would the same happens for MA(q)?

  • Take MA(1). We have \[ X_{t+1} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_{t+1} + \theta_1 e_t . \] Since \(e_{t+1}\) is uncorrelated new innovation (error) with mean 0, we would guess that the best predictor may look like \[ \hat X(1) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm - \theta_1 e_t . \]

  • \(e_t\) is yesterday’s innovation. It has already been generated, but it’s not observable. Then we can replace it with our invertible representation, \[ \hat X(1) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm - \theta_1 \hat e_t, \hspace15mm \hat e_t = \sum_{i=1}^n \pi_i X_{t-i}. \]

  • For MA(1), we know \(\pi_i\) are \[ \hat X(1) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm - \theta_1 \big(\pi_0 X_t + \pi_1 X_{t-1} + \pi_2 X_{t-2} + \cdots + \pi_{t-1} X_{1} \big) \\\\ \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm - \theta_1 \big(X_t + \theta_1 X_{t-1} + \theta_1^2 X_{t-2} + \cdots + \theta_1^{t-1} X_{1} \big) \\\\ \] This actually turns out to be best linear predictor for \(X_{t+1}\). (minimum MSE)



AR with non-causal \(\phi_1\).

  • Nothing is lost: We assume that our ARMA model is causal and invertible. However if they are not, you can always rewrite the ARMA into causal and invertible ARMA with new set of white noise.


  • Suppose our AR(1), \[ Y_t = \phi_1 Y_{t-1} + e_t \] has \(|\phi_1|>1\). Then this is not causal AR. Suppose there’s an stationary solution to this equation. ACVF formula is still valid, and \[ \gamma(0) = \frac{\sigma^2}{1-\phi_1^2}, \hspace10mm \gamma(h) = \phi_1^{|h|} \gamma(0) \]

  • Then, you can rewite this AR(1) as \[ Y_t = \frac{1}{\phi_1} Y_{t-1} + \epsilon_t \] where \(\epsilon_t\) is another WN\((0,\sigma_{\epsilon}^2)\).

  • “New” WN sequence is \[ \epsilon_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm Y_t - \frac{1}{\phi_1} Y_{t-1}. \]

  • Let’s see ACVF of \(\epsilon_t\) to see if it’s really WN. \[ \begin{align} \gamma(1) &= E(\epsilon_t \, \epsilon_{t-1}) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm E\bigg[\Big( Y_t - \frac{1}{\phi_1} Y_{t-1} \Big) \Big(Y_{t-1} - \frac{1}{\phi_1} Y_{t-2} \Big)\bigg] \\\\ &= \hspace3mm E( Y_t Y_{t-1} ) - \frac{1}{\phi_1} E( Y_t Y_{t-2} ) - \frac{1}{\phi_1} E( Y_{t-1}^2) + \frac{1}{\phi_1^2} E( Y_{t-1} Y_{t-2} ) \\\\ &= \hspace3mm \gamma(1) - \frac{1}{\phi_1} \gamma(2) - \frac{1}{\phi_1} \gamma(0) + \frac{1}{\phi_1^2} \gamma(1) \\\\ &= \hspace3mm \phi_1 \gamma(0) - \frac{1}{\phi_1} \phi_1^2 \gamma(0) - \frac{1}{\phi_1} \gamma(0) + \frac{1}{\phi_1^2} \phi_1 \gamma(0) &= \hspace3mm 0 \end{align} \]

  • \(\gamma(h)\) \(h>1\) cancells out simillarly.


  • Variance of \(\epsilon_t\) is \[ \begin{align} V(\epsilon_t) &= \hspace3mm E\bigg[\Big( Y_t - \frac{1}{\phi_1} Y_{t-1} \Big)^2 \bigg] \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm E( Y_t^2 ) - 2 \frac{1}{\phi_1} E( Y_t Y_{t-1} ) + \frac{1}{\phi_1^2} E( Y_{t-1}^2) \\ \\ &= \hspace3mm \gamma(0) - 2 \frac{1}{\phi_1} \gamma(1) + \frac{1}{\phi_1^2} \gamma(0) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \gamma(0) \Big( 1 - 2 + \frac{1}{\phi_1^2}\Big) \\ \\ &= \hspace3mm \frac{\sigma^2}{1-\phi_1^2} \Big( \frac{1}{\phi_1^2} - 1\Big) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \frac{\sigma^2}{1-\phi_1^2} \Big( \frac{1-\phi_1^2}{\phi_1^2} \Big) \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \frac{\sigma^2}{\phi_1^2} \end{align} \]

  • So the stationary solution to \[ Y_t = \phi_1 Y_{t-1} + e_t \hspace5mm \mbox{ with } e_t \sim \mbox{WN}(0,\sigma^2) \] And \[ Y_t = \frac{1}{\phi_1} Y_{t-1} + \epsilon_t \hspace5mm \mbox{ with } \epsilon_t \sim \mbox{WN}(0,\sigma^2/\phi_1^2) \] are the same. This is why we don’t consider non-causal ARMA process.



Summary

  • MA(\(q\)) process is defiend as \[ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm (1 - \theta_1 B - \theta_2 B^2 - \cdots - \theta_q B^q) e_t. \\ \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \Theta(B) e_t \] where \(\Theta(z)\) is the characteristic polynomial of MA(\(q\)).

  • MA(\(q\)) has ACF that cuts-off after lag \(q\), and PACF that decays down.

  • MA(\(q\)) has mean of 0. Theoretical ACVF: \[ \gamma(h) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} \sigma^2 (1+\theta_1^2 \cdots + \theta_q^2) & \mbox{ if } h=0 \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_1 + \theta_2 \theta_1 + \theta_3 \theta_2 + \cdots + \theta_{q-1} \theta_{q}) & \mbox{ if } h=1 \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_2 + \theta_3 \theta_1 + \cdots + \theta_{q-2} \theta_{q}) & \mbox{ if } h=2 \\ \vdots & \\ \sigma^2 (-\theta_q ) & \mbox{ if } h=q \\ 0 & \mbox{ if } |h|>q\\ \end{array} \right. \] \[ \rho(h) = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} 1 & \mbox{ if } h=0 \\ \gamma(h) / \gamma(0) & \mbox{ if } -q \leq h \leq q \\ 0 & \mbox{ if } |h|> q \\ \end{array} \right. \]

  • You can find code for Theoretical ACF and ACVF of MA(q) on page .

  • You can find code for Simulating MA(\(q\)) process and looking at Saompe ACF and PACF on page .

  • MA(\(q\)) process is defiend with equation \[ X_t = \Theta(B) e_t \] you can check the roots of the characteristic polynomial \[ \Theta(z) = 1 + \theta_1 z + \theta_2 z^2 + \cdots + \theta_q z^q. \] If all root are outside of the (complex) unit circle, then MA(\(q\)) admits a invertible representation.

  • Invertible representation allows to write today’s error using infinite sum of past observations. \[ e_t = \sum_{i=0}^\infty X_{t-i} \]

  • Bcause we can’t directly observe \(e_t\), invertibility is importatnt in calculating residuals and forecasts.
